(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 13 :title "Chapter 13 — Algebraic data" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/13-algebraic-data.md" :size 5477 :sha256 "5e5cfbbd0aab9dec" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-13\ntitle: Algebraic data\nbook: reference\nchapter: 13\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [wittgenstein-tractatus, jung, lacan, peirce, popper, freud, wittgenstein-late, searle]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 12-symbolic-differentiation\nnext: 14-a-small-typechecker\n---\n\n# Chapter 13 — Algebraic data\n\nScheme doesn't ship with algebraic data types the way ML or Haskell\ndo — but it can express them. Records with a tag field, patterns\nthat dispatch on the tag, and a discipline for who constructs and\nwho destructs. This chapter shows how to build the classical\nalgebraic data shape in Scheme and why the discipline is worth\nkeeping even when the language doesn't force it.\n\nThe example: a small expression language with `num`, `add`, `mul`,\n`let`, and `var`. Same shape as the symbolic-differentiation\nexercise from Chapter 12, but this time we'll formalize the\nconstructors and destructors and write a tiny evaluator.\n\n## The tag-based record\n\n```scheme\n(define (num n)       (list 'num n))\n(define (add a b)     (list 'add a b))\n(define (mul a b)     (list 'mul a b))\n(define (letex v e b) (list 'let v e b))\n(define (var v)       (list 'var v))\n\n(define (tag-of expr) (car expr))\n(define (args-of expr) (cdr expr))\n```\n\nEach constructor puts the tag first, followed by the payload. The\ntag is a symbol; the payload varies by type. Any consumer that\ndispatches on `tag-of` can pattern-match.\n\n## The destructors\n\n```scheme\n(define (num-value n)     (cadr n))\n(define (add-left a)      (cadr a))\n(define (add-right a)     (caddr a))\n(define (mul-left m)      (cadr m))\n(define (mul-right m)     (caddr m))\n(define (let-var l)       (cadr l))\n(define (let-expr l)      (caddr l))\n(define (let-body l)      (cadddr l))\n(define (var-name v)      (cadr v))\n```\n\nEvery constructor has matching destructors. The discipline: only\ndestructors touch positional indices; the rest of the program uses\nthe named accessors. If the layout changes, you touch destructors,\nnot consumers.\n\n## The evaluator\n\n```scheme\n(define (eval-expr expr env)\n  (case (tag-of expr)\n    ((num) (num-value expr))\n    ((add) (+ (eval-expr (add-left expr) env)\n              (eval-expr (add-right expr) env)))\n    ((mul) (* (eval-expr (mul-left expr) env)\n              (eval-expr (mul-right expr) env)))\n    ((let) (let ((v (let-var expr))\n                 (val (eval-expr (let-expr expr) env)))\n             (eval-expr (let-body expr) (cons (cons v val) env))))\n    ((var) (cdr (assq (var-name expr) env)))\n    (else  (error \"unknown expression\" expr))))\n```\n\n`case` dispatches on `tag-of`. Each branch destructures and\nrecurses. `let` extends the environment; `var` looks up. Same\nshape as the metacircular evaluator (Chapter 6) but scoped down.\n\n## Running it\n\n```scheme\n;; (let x = 3 in (x + 4) * x)\n(define example\n  (letex 'x\n         (num 3)\n         (mul (add (var 'x) (num 4))\n              (var 'x))))\n\n(eval-expr example '())\n;; => 21\n```\n\nThe tree runs. It's small, it's readable, it composes.\n\n## Why the discipline\n\nNothing in Scheme forces the tag discipline. You could reach into\n`(add 1 2)` with `cadr` and get `1` directly, no destructor\nneeded. But once you do, every consumer knows the layout, and\nchanging the layout means finding every consumer. With\ndestructors, the layout is a secret held by one function per\nfield.\n\nThis is the same discipline that record types enforce in ML. In\nScheme it's *optional* and thus load-bearing on style. When you\nkeep it, the code becomes composable; when you don't, the code\nbecomes brittle.\n\n## Pattern-matching sugar\n\nSome Schemes ship pattern-matchers; a simple one:\n\n```scheme\n(define-syntax match-expr\n  (syntax-rules (num add mul let var)\n    ((_ e ((num n)         body1) rest ...)\n     (if (eq? (tag-of e) 'num)\n         (let ((n (num-value e))) body1)\n         (match-expr e rest ...)))\n    ((_ e ((add a b)       body1) rest ...)\n     (if (eq? (tag-of e) 'add)\n         (let ((a (add-left e)) (b (add-right e))) body1)\n         (match-expr e rest ...)))\n    ;; ... etc for mul, let, var, and an else clause\n    ))\n```\n\nWith `match-expr`, the evaluator body reads a little cleaner:\n\n```scheme\n(define (eval2 e env)\n  (match-expr e\n    ((num n)         n)\n    ((add a b)       (+ (eval2 a env) (eval2 b env)))\n    ((mul a b)       (* (eval2 a env) (eval2 b env)))\n    ((let v ex b)    (eval2 b (cons (cons v (eval2 ex env)) env)))\n    ((var v)         (cdr (assq v env)))))\n```\n\nThe macro hides the tag-check and destructuring inside itself.\n\n## Sakura's register on ADTs in Scheme\n\nShe builds them when the domain deserves them — an expression\nlanguage, a shopping cart, an order state machine. She doesn't\ntag-record every list; that's cargo-cult. The rule of thumb: if\nthere's more than one shape of thing in the same slot, tag them.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> Algebraic data in Scheme is a discipline, not a feature. The\n> language doesn't force it. When I use it, my code composes;\n> when I don't, my code brittles. So I keep the discipline where\n> it earns its keep.\n\n## Exercises\n\n1. Extend the language with `if`: `(if condition then else)`.\n2. Extend with functions: `(fun (v) body)` and `(app f arg)`.\n3. Write a pretty-printer that walks the tree and produces\n   Scheme-like output.\n4. Add a static-shape checker: it walks the tree and returns\n   errors for `(add num string)` before evaluation.\n")
